<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="197" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1771,2012]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1843,1868]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet is a noun in apposition that refers to the ecosystem where the species was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="197" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1771,2012]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1915,1940]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName authority="Martinez &amp; Galvis, 2017" authorityName="Martinez &amp; Galvis" authorityYear="2017" box="[434,543,1916,1939]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hypaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="5" pageNumber="197" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varzea" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[434,543,1916,1939]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">H. varzea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[550,639,1915,1940]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[550,639,1915,1940]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be recognized from those of the remaining species of the genus by their large embolic projection (ep) in the male palpal bulb, wide and short RTA, together with the absence of the cheliceral mastidia (
<figureCitation box="[377,507,1987,2012]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1343,1366]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,218,1282]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,210,1294]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 22. H. varzea sp. nov. 17 – 20 male holotype (MPUJ-ENT 46827), left palp, 17 prolateral view; 18 ventral view; 19 retroventral view; 20 retrolateral view; 21 same, frontal view; 22 same, dorsal view. e = embolus; ep = embolar projection base; RTA = retrolateral tibial apophysis; RvTA = retroventral tibial apophysis; Spe = spermophore." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/818624/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">Figs 17–21</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/818624/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="198" targetBox="[160,1423,218,1282]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1343,1427]" pageId="6" pageNumber="198">
